    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c4ad1538_721488a6",
        "filename": "util/linux/elf_symbol_table_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 47,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-06-23T21:42:24Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "You aren’t affirmatively checking for the end of the symbol table at all.\n\nIdeally you’d know how long the symbol table is, and only allow yourself to read within those bounds. But that means you’d need to look at the section headers instead of/in addition to the dynamic table.\n\nThat’d also be nice for ElfImageReader::ReadStringTableAtOffset(), to make sure that you don’t read outside of .dynstr.",
      "revId": "ee519d37bcefddd4852adf8bf9f0cde9c1a4b551",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "1e820563_c3f25be9",
        "filename": "util/linux/elf_symbol_table_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 47,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-06-24T00:11:03Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e Ideally you’d know how long the symbol table is, and only allow yourself to read within those bounds. But that means you’d need to look at the section headers instead of/in addition to the dynamic table.\n\nBut you also told me that the loader wouldn’t normally make section headers available, so…\n\nIs there some other way to bound these? How do ld.so implementations interpret this and know when they’ve reached the end?",
      "parentUuid": "c4ad1538_721488a6",
      "revId": "ee519d37bcefddd4852adf8bf9f0cde9c1a4b551",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "de0a4851_8c50c9f3",
        "filename": "util/linux/elf_symbol_table_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 47,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-06-24T00:18:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The number of entries is available in the .hash or .gnu.hash sections. I don\u0027t think I\u0027ve seen it available elsewhere yet. My plan was to make using .hash/.gnu.hash sections a high priority TODO once things are working end-to-end.",
      "parentUuid": "1e820563_c3f25be9",
      "revId": "ee519d37bcefddd4852adf8bf9f0cde9c1a4b551",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "70abde95_6964d175",
        "filename": "util/linux/elf_symbol_table_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 49,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-06-23T21:42:24Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "We need to nail this down a little bit more.\n\nWe don’t want to return undefined symbols (st_shndx \u003d\u003d SHN_UNDEF) from here, although they will show up in the dynamic symbol table. And if you find anything SHN_ABS, you wouldn’t want to apply the load bias fix-up.\n\nThe Mach-O symbol table reader nails this down by not having a generically-named “GetSymbol” but instead “LookUpExternalDefinedSymbol”. Mach-O doesn’t have separate dynamic and non-dynamic symbol tables, so the “external” bit is intended to exclude things that wouldn’t appear in ELF’s dynamic symbol table anyway. But since this ELF symbol table reader isn’t specific to the dynamic symbol table, it may be worth nailing this down to ELF_ST_BIND(st_info) \u003d\u003d STB_GLOBAL or STB_WEAK. ELF_ST_TYPE(st_info) \u003d\u003d STT_OBJECT, STT_FUNC, or STT_COMMON also.\n\nSome of this may mean that you need to return a little more information from here, so that the caller can decide whether to compute load bias, etc. If things get to the point where we’re dealing with STT_TLS, that’d be relevant too, since those have a whole different interpretation.",
      "revId": "ee519d37bcefddd4852adf8bf9f0cde9c1a4b551",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
